data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed for this code.**

Your `SimpleWorker` class only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep`. None of these APIs are affected by the `Thread.Abort` removal in modern .NET — they work identically on .NET 8.

There are no references to:
- `Thread.Abort` / `thread.Abort()`
- `ThreadAbortException`
- `Thread.ResetAbort`
- `Thread.Interrupt`

This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

---

**Optional modernization (unrelated to Thread.Abort):** You could simplify this with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run` + `Task.WhenAll`, which would also give you natural `CancellationToken` support if you need it later:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items,
    CancellationToken token = default)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, token, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        await Task.Delay(100, ct); // replaces Thread.Sleep
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

But again, this is purely optional — your existing code requires no changes for .NET 8.
